jobs.description:
Michael managed the Office of General Counsel at Gosford City Council in the period up to the amalgamation of the former Council with Wyong Shire Council in May 2016 to create the Central Coast Council.

During this time, Michael led a small team and was responsible for managing all legal work for the Council, including:

•	all Land and Environment Court proceedings, including section 34 conciliation processes;
•	providing advice to the property, procurement and governance units within the Council, as well as Councillors;
•	 briefing external consultants, solicitors and counsel; and
•	 providing advice to the Council relating to the legal implications of the amalgamation process.

Michael specialises in environment and planning law and primarily provides advice to large private and public sector entities about the approvals needed to facilitate major projects in New South Wales and Queensland.  

His recent legal experience includes:

•	WestConnex Delivery Authority - advising in relation to the $2.7 billion design and construction contract for the M4 East Motorway;

•	Seqwater – advising on compliance matters under State water legislation and throughout the Queensland Floods Commission of Inquiry process; 

•	advising bidding consortia in relation to planning and environmental obligations and risks associated with recent Government privatisations, including the Sydney Desalination Plant and Bayswater and Liddell power stations; 

•	Xstrata Coal / GVK Hancock – managing objection proceedings commenced on climate change grounds for the Wandoan and Alpha coal projects; and

•	negotiating and drafting infrastructure agreements in Queensland for Government clients and voluntary planning agreements in New South Wales for developers in Western Sydney.

Michael presented at the 2014 PIA (Qld) State Conference on the practical implications of the proposed new planning regimes in NSW and Queensland. He presented at the 2014 QELA Conference and the 2013 PIA (Qld) State Conference about the implications of the planning reform agendas on resource projects.  

He also presented at the 2012 PIA National Congress about the land use planning recommendations contained in the Queensland Floods Commission of Inquiry final report and was named a Runner Up at the Minister's Town Planning Prize 2012 for his recommendations on regulatory responses to the 2011 Queensland floods.

In 2015, Michael initiated the PIA (NSW) Planning Reform Series which continues to be hosted at Allens.

Leading revitalisation of the Cleveland CBD.

Leading a review of Council Surplus lands.

Leading the Toondah Harbour and Weinam Creek PDAS as follows

Leading the planning and development of Toondah Harbour (67 ha including 49 ha over water); and Weinam Creek (42 ha including 6 ha over water).  The projects valued at over $1 billion, to create over 1000 jobs.  

Project managed and co authored the Development Scheme.  The Development Scheme identified residential, mixed use, marina, and vehicle ferry infrastructure. It contains a Land Use Plan, Infrastructure Plan, Implementation Plan, and Sustainability Plan.

Carried out management of development criteria for the Development Scheme and planning for infrastructure .  Infrastructure included:
•	Ferry terminals forming the role as “Gateways” to Stradbroke Island with capacity for at least 2 vehicle ferry operators (70,000 trips pa) and 2 passenger operators (500,000 trips pa);
•	Capital dredging to straighten and widen navigation channels;
•	Capital dredging to create a marina for up to 400 berths;
•	Reclamation for developable land for  retail, commercial, marine industry;
•	Car parks with ferry terminals, ;
•	Roads, water, sewerage, power, drainage, 
•	Contiguous boardwalk promenade ;
•	Accommodation for existing and required community uses. 

Commissioned comprehensive studies. The outcome was the finalisation of studies for land use and infrastructure for use in detailed planning and structure planning.

Together with internal staff, led Council's responsibilities in preparation of Expression of Interest EOI documents.  The EOI was to enable a shortlist of proponents to be selected.    

Identified Council's requirements for the Request for Proposals (RFP).  The RFP was required to facilitate developers identifying the elements of the land use and additional infrastructure to be provided, and to be negotiated through governance arrangements e.g. a “special purpose vehicle” and ‘Local representative committee”.

