I lead the Office of the General Counsel at the Department of Communication and the Arts. I have significant experience in telecommunications, media and competition law, including significant experience across the telecommunications, general infrastructure, financial services, FMCG and technology sectors. I have expertise in negotiating and drafting commercial agreements (including IT outsourcing, procurement and supply) and privacy law. 

I thrive on new challenges and working within a team environment. I am an in demand presenter, known for my enthusiasm and ability to communicate complex concepts in an engaging and immediate way. I am enthusiastic, financially literate, remain calm under pressure and am known for my clear and effective communication, efficiency and organisation.

Career highlights include:
•	General Counsel (formerly Deputy General Counsel) at the Department of Communication and the Arts 
•	Spending 2014 on secondment at nbn (the Government Business Enterprise formed to roll out the national broadband network), a transformative year in the company’s history when a significant change in policy and culture was implemented; 
•	Advising UGL Premas in relation to the world first separation of the Singaporean duct and exchange network;
•	Advising the National Competition Council in relation to Fortescue Metals Group’s application for access to certain private railway lines owned and/or operated by BHP Billiton and Rio Tinto in the Pilbara, including proceedings before the High Court of Australia;
•	Advising Pacific National (Asciano) in relation to proceedings ultimately determined by the High Court of Australia in relation to rail access agreements in NSW; and
•	Advising Fortescue Metals Group in relation to their constitutional challenge to the MRRT.
